column168: On 12/01/2017, at 1928hrs, personnel in the CSXT Pinoca Yard discovered UTLX201666, a loaded  tank car of UN3802, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified by David Callahan (978-840-2139)of Mexichem Specialty Compounds.  Marion Environmental Incorporated, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a secondary closure plug not installed and the vapor line valve was not closed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. David Callahan 978-840-2139. Contractor personnel installed a plug and closed the valve and wiped down the affected area.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 390  NARRI:5(5+1+5) x (2+0)  = 110

column168: UN3115 "Organic Peroxide Type D, Liquid, Temperature Controlled "material leaked from the trailer floor to the asphalt of the truck stop.(8) 5-gallon poly pails leaked a total of 1 pint to ground outside the trailer and less than 1 pint inside the trailer primarily to the tops of the pails and down one rung of the corrugated floor. Cause of the leak was one pail in particular which required a quarter-turn to close the cap and that (8) containers had caps that required tightening. It is estimated that the containers had faulty caps/seals causing the initial release and that the secondary release was caused by jostling of the freight during transit, creating the small crease/puncture in the bottom of the pail

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 12/07/2017, 1335 hours, a Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspector in the CSXT Wilsmere Yard discovered GATX 72080, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified. (CHEMTREC Report #2017120700122). HEPACO LLC, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the non-reclosing pressure relief device disc ruptured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel replaced the frangible disc in kind and removed/neutralized all spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI:100

column168: Vehicle was traveling south on Palmyra Bellegrove Road and failed to negociate a 90 degree left hand turn.  The vehicle left the roadway after encountering the right shoulder of the highhway and rolled over 3/4 of the way, coming to rest on its left (drivers) side in a harvested corn field.  There was no product release and no injuries to the driver.  In house emergency response team immediately went to the site of the accident to determine the safety of the recovery effort.  Vehicle was righted and towed from the scene after 2 hours without incident.
column169: Result of the accident was purely driver error, but although the driver was traveling at the posted speed limit for the road, the driver failed to act quickly enough to the approaching curve in reducing speed to safely negociate the turn.  The driver, although having a class B CDL, has minimal experience with a heavy truck and less experience driving a liquid load.  More experience, not to mention common sense, would have prevent this incident.

column168: On 12/18/2017, at 1906 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered TILX 319475, a loaded tank car of Cyclopentane, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper and National Response Center were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2017-1218-00194). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the sample line valve in the open position and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Mike McCoy of Odjfell Terminal, phone 843-714-6330. Contractor personnel closed the sample line valve, tightened the secondary closure plug, and cleaned all spilled material from the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code: 145  NARRI:80

column168: While loading packages, a driver noticed a cubic yard box (CYB) from a previous pick up leaking onto the floor of the box truck. The driver and company technician both donned the correct personal protective equipment and repacked the paint cans loaded within this leaking CYB into a new UN rated CYB, taking care to check the individual paint can closures, making sure the cans were placed upright and secured from movement, and added the appropriate absorbents to the bottom of the box as a protective measure. All waste materials generated from the cleanup were placed inside the new CYB, including the leaking package.     The leaking CYB was found to contain inner paint cans that were not tightly closed, and was also found to have a small puncture (of an undetermined origin) in the liner. No absorbent had been used while originally packaging.     This was reported to the State of CT DEEP on 12/04/2017 at 13:51 EST, report #201706302.
column169: At the time this package was placed into transportation, there was no evidence of a release or package integrity issue. We have contacted the generator, and asked them to take greater care in packaging this waste paint material, paying special attention to the each paint can closure, the orientation of these cans within the cubic yard box, and the use of absorbents at the bottom of each box. We have also asked the generator to ask its personnel to take greater care when placing these cans into the cubic yard box,  so as not to cause any tears, abrasions, or punctures to the inner liner.

column168: PKG DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE UNLOAD . PKG WAS SMASHED BY A BULK PKG . DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET WAS UTILIZED. PKG AND RELATED DEBRIS TRANSPORTED TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

THE TRAILER WAS STAGED ON DOCK 6, UPON OPENING THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER THE UNLOADER NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE UNDER A FIVE GALLON DRUM. HE THEN LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. HIS SUPERVISOR THEN CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER, FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND THE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, CLEANED UP THE SPILL. THE EQUIPMENT WAS DECONTAMINATED UTILIZING THE DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: RESPONDER ROB RAIO WAS CALLED TO COLLECT A LEAKING PACKAGE ON PD 13. UPON INSPECTION, THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE DISINFECTANT BEARING HAZMAT MARKINGS OXIDIZER 5.1 AND CORROSIVE 8. I OPENED THE CARTON AND DISCOVERED THAT ONE GALLON WAS LEAKING FROM THE VENTED CAP. I SOLIDIFIED THE LIQUID FROM THE ONE GALLON THAT WAS LEAKING AND PLACED THE CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD AND WOODEN STIRRING STICK IN THE BAG. THE MIXTURE BEGAN TO SMOKE, SO I TOOK IT OUTSIDE TO A SAFE LOCATION AWAY FROM PEOPLE. SUPERVISOR SHAWN MURPHY EXAMINED THE BAG AND REMOVED THE STIRRING STICK AND CARDBOARD; HE FOUND THAT THE STICK WAS HOT. THE SMOKE BEGAN TO DIMINISH; A FEW HOURS LATER WE DETERMINED THAT IT WAS SAFE TO BRING THE PACKAGE BACK INSIDE TO PROCESS IT THROUGH DMP.
column169: ENSURE THAT VENTED CAPS FUNCTION PROPERLY PRIOR TO SHIPPING.

column168: While unloading a trailer full of waste for storage and consolidation, facility personnel noticed a drum was leaking. This happened inside a box van, and only the floor of that trailer was impacted; no soil, water, or asphalt were affected. An emergency response crew was summoned. This crew, wearing the correct personal protective equipment, found the drum to have a small pinhole near the bottom chime, which suggests interior corrosion or and off specification waste stream. The crew over packed the leaking drum into a UN rated salvage over pack drum, along with all the waste generated from the cleanup of the trailer floor. The drum continued onto to its final destination without further incident.     The release did not meet the reporting requirements for the State of Ohio.
column169: At the time this package was placed into transportation, there was no evidence of a release or issue. We  have asked the generator to investigate the possibility that this waste stream was off-specification. Also, we have asked them to take greater care in inspecting drums prior to use, with an emphasis on inspecting the condition of the drum interiors, particularly on any drum that has been used previously for another product or waste stream.

column168: On 12/21/17 at 1234 hours, FRA Inspector Lester Rawls in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered UTLX12274, a residue tank car of phosphoric acid solution with the vapor line valve in the open position and the vapor line plug not installed. The car was isolated and the emergency contact on waybill (PCS Sales, Paul Duckeworth (706)469-1301) was notified.  The shipper is CORPORACION QUIMICA OMEGA out of Mexico and no contact info was available. Specialized Professional Services Inc. (SPSI), a CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve in the open position and the vapor line plug not installed. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the consignee/ car emergency contact Paul Duckeworth (706)469-1301. SPSI closed the vapor line valve and installed tool tight the vapor line plug.  The car was released.        NAR Cause Code: 380 – valve open and cap not installed    5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70 NARRI     New Orleans, LA – 12/21/17 – UTLX12274– Phosphoric Acid Solution

column168: Visual conditions were clear, sunshine with a cloudy overcast. There was minimal traffic on the road. No ice present & dry road conditions. Driver described product surging after he'd come out of a curve. He explained that the truck was swaying side to side causing him to drift into another lane. As he began to drift into another lane he turned his wheel to correct the direction of travel; the truck responded and he attempted to correct the action again. He explained that the truck began to head towards a guard wall which protects traffic from going into the Jones Falls Stream. Upon seeing the direction of travel he stated that he applied the brakes, thus resulting in him losing control of the vehicle. Phillip was taken to Sinai Hospital 2401 West Belvedere Ave. Baltimore, Maryland where he was seen by Tara L. Ong MD. Phillip sustained no injuries and was provided a note stating that he could return to work 12/29/17. The DriveCam footage was retrieved from truck 1043 and reviewed. The footage displayed Phillip dozing off behind the wheel. The vehicle began to drift towards the guard wall, and Phillip overcompensated his attempted recovery which caused the rollover. Phillip clocked in at 06:10 am on Tuesday 12/26/17. Phillip did not work Sunday 12/24/17 and did not work Monday 12/25/17. The product released into the Jones Falls Stream in being collected at 1901 Falls Rd. Baltimore, MD. This area was selected by the heads of MDE and ACE Environmental to provide the least amount of contact with the public and to minimize environmental harm. ACE Environmental will provide us with updates on the progress of the cleanup. The Coast Guard has been informed of the cleanup plans and collection point, as the Jones Falls Steam runs into a major body of water.

column168: On December 20, 2017 at 1554 hours, personnel at CSXT Queensgate Yard in Cincinnati, OH discovered NATX 37605, a loaded UN 1090 - Acetone, PGII tank car to have released product from the top area of the car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Ineos Phenol, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2017-12-20-00215. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Environmental Management Services was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined 3 of 6 manway bolts were less than tool tight and one of the swing bolts had 3 washers in place to help secure the nut. The car was secured until a replacement swing bolt could be obtained for proper securement.

column168: A WG Saterlee and Sons 406 tanker hauling 6,000 gals of NA1993 Diesel was involved in a single-vehicle rollover accident on Eighty Four road in Eighty Four, PA. The accident was the result of an apparent mechanical issue with the steering column causing the driver to lose control and roll his tanker onto the center of the 2 lane roadway. Approximately 40 gallons of diesel released from leaking vent lines/ valves over a 5 hour duration while it was on its side. Hazmat contractors and the local fire department arrived onsite to transfer the remaining product into a relief tanker, up-right the tanker and cleanup the spill.

Event # 67459.. No package failure..    Driver states that when he arrived at the consignee warehouse the tanks were full..   A consignee employee pulled in one of their trailers and filled it to make room for the product in our trailer.. When consignee employee was done he told IVD to go ahead and unload..     The area where the unloading takes place has three (3) pumps lined up.. The consignee employee used the 3rd pump to load his trailer and left a valve open that goes from the 2nd pump to the 3rd pump..     Driver hooked up to the 1st pump.. He immediately saw diesel coming out of the pump area.. He shut down immediately..  He states that the release of the product lasted less than 1 minute and he estimates somewhere between 25 and 30 gallons were released..     Spill was cleaned up with absorbent pads..

column168: Driver left the terminal loaded with 4,000 gallons of jet fuel. As driver was navigating down Murphy Road in Belton, SC the driver allowed the truck to travel off of the road edge on the right side, causing the truck to track off of the roadway and result in an overturn. The driver immediately notified 911 which responded. The driver then notified his Safety Officer, which immediately dispatched a remediation crew. The tank was leaking out of a crushed vapor valve, which the fire department placed a pan under to collect the leak until remediation crew could arrive. Remediation crew cut two 4" holes in the side of the tank to allow pumping out of the product in the tank. Once the drill broke the seal of the tank, the product started to leak but was caught by the drain pans. Once the vehicle was pumped completely out, the truck was turned back over and towed away. The environmental crew excavated a small area where the soil was contaminated, tests were conducted to make sure all product was removed, and then the excavation was backfilled and restored to its original condition. COmplete remediation was completed 12/28/2017.
column169: This incident was attributable to driver error. However, changes have been made to avoid smaller roads (such as Murphy Rd) around the terminals in this area. Drivers will be using larger state roads for travel to and from the Belton Terminal.

column168: LTL Driver picked up shipment of two drums and 3 IBC's (Two were other materials) from shipper Hubbard hall. Driver secured drums and IBC to wall with ratchet straps at approximately 48" level off floor. location was near front of trailer.    Driver then made multiple pickups over a 3 to 4 hour span, proceeding towards home terminal. At last pickup 60 minutes from home terminal, he noticed that chemical smell in trailer had increased, but was still in tolerable range, which is not out of the norm with these moves.     On arrival to terminal, strong, irritating, chemical odor was detected immediately upon opening of rollup door, and there was liquid of unknown origin on floor at rear. Supervisor on duty immediately contacted me, I then provided guidance to remove trailer from door and place in yard to minimize exposure. Specific instruction was given to place unit away from storm drains or unpaved areas. Shop personnel was prepared to place dirt and absorbent materials on the asphalt, as well as having containers ready to catch any significant leakage from trailer. These steps were not necessary, leakage from trailer itself was negligible.    EPS of VT was contacted, they have a facility on same street as ours, and they had staff on scene in approximately 60 minutes. They contained the material, then cleaned and neutralized residue in trailer. Material in damaged IBC was transferred to an intact vessel. EPS moved all waste material from site on manifest 009844284.    EPS discovered that ratchet mechanism of strap used to secure IBC to vehicle twisted inward, allowing stamped-steel edge of mechanism to chafe/cut into IBC at a height of approximately 48" from floor. Material in IBC above that height then leaked through slice.    Duration of leak is unknown and appears to have slowed significantly once vehicle motion stop. We believe material loss to be less than 15 gallons.
column169: Guidance given to driver in regards to using protective material, such as cardboard, a wooden pallet that pulls mechanism away from IBC, or utilizing blocking/bracing vs strap when the above methods are not possible.

column168: Our Driver (Berner) was headed north on 27 and coming out of a small curve in road and another truck headed south lost control and cross travel lanes and rolled his truck in the north bound lanes after overcorrecting and was blocking both lanes of the north bound roadway. It was approx. 530 am and it was dark and a light fog. Berner driver coming out of the curve did not have ample time to avoid the truck in the roadway (no lights on disabled truck) and tried to avoid him and left roadway into median where truck rolled over in median causing material to leak out. Notifications were made immediately to appropriate authorities (NRC, Florida state warning point, SWS Cleanup). Approx. 2700 gallons of Gasoline and Diesel fuel were released.
column169: It is not known for certain but from the information received it was alleged that the driver who's truck crossed travel lanes and rolled over into the northbound lanes had put his truck in cruise control (drivers words) and lost control. It is our fear that the driver may have fell asleep. I do not know that to be certain but it is my fear. The only recommendation I could make would be to not have cruise control in these trucks and that in my opinion better lighting of the roadway may have helped.

On 12/28/17 as poly totes were being loaded onto a van trailer a Clean Harbors employee notice a small amount of liquid leaking from the valve area of one of the totes.  The employee immediately applied sorbent material to the spill area.  Clean Harbors F/S was called to transfer the contents to another tote.  The cleanup material along with the totes were sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Safety Kleen reached out to the customer and reminded them that any type of package being offered for transportation must be properly closed and there cannot be any integrity issues including valve assemblies.

column168: The driver did not disconnect his loading hose after filling the cargo tank.  Crude oil spilled on the ground adjacent to the loading header from the hose.  Crude oil also spilled from the cargo tank through the loading hose as the truck pulled away.    The spill was cleaned up and remediated as per Kansas Department of Health and Environment requirements.
column169: The employee was placed off duty awaiting corrective action pending the review and investigation.

column168: On December 13, 2017, a Veolia driver loaded a cargo tank truck at the customer site and proceeded driving.  At 4:37 PM, the driver was pulled over by an Ohio Highway Patrol Officer who noticed material leaking from the rear of the truck. The driver pulled over and determined the source of the leak.  The driver pulled vacuum in the truck, stopping the leak, and tightened the rear hatch lugs by 1/8th of a turn.  The release of hazardous waste from the truck amounted to 6 liquid quarts.
column169: The Veolia driver was counseled and retrained on the importance of placing the vacuum truck under pressure prior to tightening the rear hatch lugs when loading.

column168: SCOT FELMLEE ALTA TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT INVOLVING A FUEL TRANSPORT AND A PU TRUCK 5 MILE WEST OF BLANCA CO ON HWY 160 AT APPX 550 AM ON 12-7-17. HE WAS LOADED WITH 9500G REGULAR E-10 PULLED FROM THE LA JUNTA COLORADO FUEL TERMINAL HEADED TO THE ALTA BULK PLANT IN ALAMOSA CO. A PICKUP TRUCK HEADING EB ON HWY 160 FAILED TO MAKE THE CURVE AND STRUCK THE WB FUEL TRANSPORT HEAD ON. THE PU RUPTURED THE TRACTORS FUEL TANK IGNITING THE TRACTOR WHICH THEN RAN OFF THE ROADWAY. MR FELMLEE WAS ABLE TO REMOVE HIMSELF FROM THE TRACTOR CAB AND EVACUATE A SHORT DISTANCE AWAY BEFORE THE GAS IN THE TRAILER IGNITED. THE PU TRUCK WAS NOT ENGULFED IN THE FLAMES AND LANDED ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY AWAY FROM THE TANKER. COHP RESPONDED ALONG WITH ALAMOSA FIRE/RESCUE. THE 9500G OF GASOLINE BURNED ALMOST COMPLETELY AND THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE COMPLETELY DESTROYED. THE PU TRUCK DRIVER AND MR FELMLEE WERE BOTH TRANSPORTED TO ALAMOSO CO HOSPITAL. BELFOR ENVIRONMENTAL WERE CONTACTED BY ALTA TRANSPORTATION AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPX 11:45AM. AFTER DETERMINING THE APPX AREA OF CONTAMINATION THEY BROUGHT IN HEAVY EQUIPMENT AND REMOVE APPX 500 CUBIC YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND DISPOSED OF AT WASTE MANAGEMENT MIDWAY LANDFILL PUEBLO COLORADO. ALL PRODUCT WAS REMOVED OFF SITE ON DEC 27 AND 28. BACK FILL AND SEEDING OF AREA WILL BE DONE WHEN WEATHER ALLOWS.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 12/15/17 (2230pt), the S. Seattle hub advised LARS that top unit JBHU281085 arrived leaking a thick yellow liquid onto the bottom container (JBHU305366), as well as the well car. The containers were deramped and placed in a safe haven area.    LARS contacted NRC Environmental to respond and remediate the leakage. JBHU281085 was waybilled containing nonplacard amounts of batteries: UN2794 and UN3480. The actual leaking material was from one of numerous undeclared hazmat materials in the load. The leak was UN1263 Paint, specifically a epoxy resin material. The source was a tightly stretchwrapped pallet of 3 gallon metal pails, which one leaked from the bottom layer.  Approximately 1 quart was under the pallet, on the floor, 1 gallon was on the exterior of the bottom container and 1/2 gal contained on the railcar. The material was hardened or hardening at time of cleanup.    The cargo was reloaded and 2 drums of recovered materials placed at the rear for shipper handling. LARS advised JB Hunt Cargo Claims (Richard) of additional undeclared hazmat products in the load, not declared but of reportable and placarding quantities.
column169: JB Hunt has been advised to confirm proper placarding with their customer: Saia Motor Frt prior to pickup. Review with Saia, the discrepancies of their waybilling to ensure future shipments are accurate and  complete.

column168: PLMX 30159 was found leaking in the BNSF Barstow trainyard.  Single droplets coming from the packing gland area of the bottom outlet valve handle.  BNSF Hazmat responder tightened packing gland 1/2 turn and leak stopped.  Estimated loss of 3 tablespoons onto railroad tie.  Spill was wiped up and car was released to service with no further remediation required.
column169: Ensure all valves, closures, and fittings are tight and secure prior to offering hazmat shipments into transportation per applicable regulations.  Re-train, raise awareness, and conduct spot audits to ensure compliance.

column168: On 12/20/17 received notification from Hub personnel at the BNSF Los Angeles IMF that unit JBHU 284506 was leaking an unknown substance from the nose section of the unit, as the assigned driver attempted to outgate the unit. In the interest of safety the unit was placed on hold from outgating and moved to the containment pit area pending interior inspection of the cargo. At the time of the interior inspection the unit was not actively leaking. Cargo inspection revealed a mix load of palletized 55 gallon drums and 5 gallon  containers stowed two rows wide one layer high. The load was secured with two plies of tyguard, laminated wood blocking at the rear two pallets, with a DID airbag applied inbetween the centerline void as a form of secondary securement. A pallet of 5 gallon containers placed at the nose section of the unit has collapsed to the left side, falling onto the adjacent pallet spilling approximately 3 ounces of product onto the adjacent pallet. The spilled product is labeled as FS ZCHLOR (UN3266) Food Industry  Chlorinated Cleaner (hazardous). It appears that the collapsed pallet had a significant centerline void space that was not secured, also it appears that the containers placed in the bottom of the pallet have failed.
column169: Shipper should take proper care in blocking and bracing loads prior to shipment per applicable regulations.

At 0430 on 12/22/2017 the GATX 22293 was involved in a sideswipe derailment in the BNSF Pasco yard in Pasco, WA which resulted in the car rolling onto its side and top, partially burying the manway and valve assemblies in the ballast.  During rerailing operations at approximately 0950 on 12/22/17 it was discovered that a small amount of product, approximately 1 gallon, had leaked from the liquid valve body.  The cause of the leak was damage incurred during the derailment as the car rolled partially onto its top, cracking the valve body.  Environmental contractor Clean Harbors was dispatched to assist with cleanup and remediation.  Car sustained significant damage and its contents will be transloaded and the car will be cleaned and dismantled.
column169: Cause of derailment is under investigation.  Pending root cause, action will be taken to prevent incidents of similar nature from occurring.  Processes and procedures will be evaluated and retraining as necessary.

column168: Neier driver received the load of materials from Clean Harbors Environmental in La Porte TX.  Driver reported preparing load paperwork for transportation, inspecting the loaded containers of materials from the rear of the trailer, and ensuring load securement bar was in place.  The driver departed the facility at approximately 1730EST and encountered slow/sporadic traffic on Highway 59.  The driver reported that as traffic began to clear, another vehicle merged into his lane and slowed down, resulting in a deceleration event to avoid collision.  The driver reported feeling load movement and seeing a mist near the trailer mud flap.  The driver immediately pulled to the emergency shoulder to investigate, contacted the emergency telephone number from the shipping document (Clean Harbors), placed out emergency triangles, and place absorbent pads where material was dripping from the trailer.  The driver then notified Neier, Inc. parties of the incident and confirmed there were no waterways or drainage systems impacted by the event.  The driver remained in contact with Clean Harbors Emergency Response after initial notification call at 1730.  Response crew arrived at the incident scene at 2000 to investigate and respond to leaking material.  The crew reported multiple drums had fallen off of the pallets, 4 drums were punctured and leaking, and a presence of standing liquid in the trailer.  The leaking drums were over-packed and standing liquid from the trailer was pumped back into one of the drums.  The trailer was cleaned and reorganized.  The impacted concrete/dirt was cleaned/removed and contained in a drum, along with used sorbents, pads, and materials.  The response crew reports completion of scene clean up at 2300.
column169: After the trailer was opened and inspected by the response crew, the Neier driver reported that there were large gaps/open spaces between packages near the middle and front of the trailer although there was not in the rear of lead near the load securement bar.  This indicates additional load securement bars should have been placed near the gaps to further secure the drums on the pallet(s), or that the packages should have been loaded closer together to prevent containers from shifting within the trailer during transit.  Proper visual inspection of containers and ensuring proper load securement was discussed with the Neier drive.  Additionally, the shipper began using multiple securement straps throughout the load, in addition to the rear load securement bar.

column168: On December 26, 2017, Landstar Inway (Reference # 415830 and 366270) notified ERTS in regards to a possible hazardous materials cargo release. According to the caller, the driver of tractor (415830) trailer (697434) rolled over-due to the steering column locking up. The freight inside the trailer is cargo. The caller indicated that local authorities are on site. Contractor indicated that Sooner Emergency was dispatched by either the Wrecker Service or local Police. Contractor indicated that there are totes in the trailer that are Sodium Hydroxide. Contractor indicated that Sooner is conducting cleanup. Contractor indicated that the trailer has (10) 330-gallon poly totes of UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide, 8, II. The contractor indicated that only (1) 330-gallon poly tote appears to be leaking at this time. Approximately 150-gallons of product has been released to the roadway. Contractor indicated that an unknown amount went into a nearby storm drain. Contractor indicated that (5) totes have been unloaded at this time. Sooner Emergency has placed down absorbent boom and absorbent materials to clean the release. Contractor indicated that Sooner has finished offloading the trailer at 1807. Sooner has used absorbent materials to clean the roadway. Contractor indicated that Sooner personnel are beginning to address the impacted drain at this time. Contractor indicated that Lenox Towing has removed the tractor trailer from the site. All cleanup activities have been finished for the night. Sooner personnel have finished and have taken all waste off site.

column168: At approximately 1936 hours, rail operator was performing 2nd “Check your 6” inspection inside the dome of a loaded propane railcar at spot #5. A “pinhole” leak was noticed where the sample valve nipple threads into the body of the railcar. Operator used an 8” pipe wrench to fix the leak. In the process, the nipple was unthreaded and completely detached from the car releasing 3,200 gallons of propane. Operator’s right forearm and right cheek were burned from contact with the escaping propane. The sample valve’s excess flow/check valve failed to seat resulting in an uncontrolled release of propane for approximately 2 hours.
column169: CF-1a Revise Railcar Loading and Bubble Testing procedures to clearly define the parameters for the type of repair or work which DCP employees as a non-AAR Certified Tank Car entity can and cannot perform per Federal Railroad Administration Tank Car Safety Initiatives Attachment A – Tank Car Maintenance (Repair) and Qualification. Government Regulations October 2017 T59.1  CF-1b Clearly communicate the requirements of the new procedures and the associated roles, responsibilities and accountabilities to all affected employees.  CF-1c Ensure all NGL rail terminals procedures incorporate the FRA Tank Car Safety requirements, if not revise procedures per CF-1a & 1b recommendations.  LL-1, 2, 3 Perform a Proactive Safeguards Analysis on the railcar loading/unloading process to identify Human Action Safeguards and list all the enabling Administrative Control Quasi-Safeguards that are used to make that Human Action Safeguard Reliable.  LL-4 Develop and implement a monthly fire monitor flow inspection schedule to be performed by all employees to provide hands-on operation of and familiarity with firewater monitors.  LL-5a Evaluate existing fall protection system against regulatory requirements, industry standards and best practices  LL-5b Implement recommended changes to rail loading fall protection based on LL-2a evaluation.  LL-5c Perform a gap analysis on fall protection systems and policies across all NGL assets with railcar operations and make recommendations  LL-6 Remove the fence. The original Homeland Security order to install the fence was based on errors and is no longer required; therefore, fence is being removed as of 12/21/2017.

column168: Valdosta, GA– 12/28/2017 – AZXX 32359 – Flammable Liquids, N.O.S.    On 12/28/2017 at 14:17, in Valdosta Yard, Valdosta, GA, CSX personnel discovered AZXX 32359, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids N.O.S (Crude Sulfate Turpentine, Alpha-Pinene), leaking from the vacuum relief valve.  The car was isolated and the shipper International Paper and the NRC (report number 1200702) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number  2017-1128-00165.  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from the vacuum relief valve.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Victoria Johnson, 910-362-3523).  Hulls Environmental replaced the vacuum relief valve with a blind flange, and International Paper filed OTMA-3 for movement to unload car.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.

column168: On December 22, 2017, at 1305 ET, ERTS received a call from Jeff Lewis of MC Tank regarding an exposure/release to a driver. At 1215 ET, an M.C. Tank driver of Truck #2547 was unloading at a customer location when he was inadvertently sprayed (estimated 1 pint to 1 quart released) with UN2582 Ferric Chloride (material being unloaded), the driver immediately took off the impacted clothing and placed them in the truck and left the site. During driving, the driver felt light-headed and dizzy, pulled over, contacted 911 and the driver has been transported to the hospital. The driver was on I-95 around exit 25 in Philadelphia, PA. HEPACO arrived on site and removed impacted clothing from the truck and a relief driver continued on transport of the material.     On December 27, 2017 at 0822 ET, M.C. Tank requested HEPACO return to the holding yard (located at 3201 North Delaware Ave in Philadelphia, PA) contractors go to the holding yard for the trailer and clean up a residual spill from the trailer that is in puddles and a Catch basin at the yard. HEPACO returned to site and it appears that the tanker released an estimated 10 Gallons of Ferric Chloride material due to a leak in the valve of the tanker. Team secured the release and changed the valve on the trailer and set up the area to have a transfer be performed into a new trailer.     On December 28th, HEPACO returned to site and performed the transfer into a relief trailer. During the transfer operation, another estimated 5 Gallons released to the asphalt of the transfer yard. HEPACO cleaned the released material and transported the waste off-site.

column168: At 1305 ET, ERTS received a call from Dupre Logistics regarding a spill in Nashville, TN at a Kroger's store. At 1230 ET, truck #377628 / trailer #22109 was unloading Gasoline at a Kroger's Gas Station, when approximately 100 Gallons of Gasoline was released to the asphalt/cement and a nearby storm drain of the area due to overfilling the pumps at the station. HEPACO was contracted to remediate the areas of impact.     The release was considered immediate and was shut off as soon as the overfill began happening. HEPACO coordinated with other on-site contractors to remove the gasoline from the storm drain and asphalt with equipment. The cargo tank was inspected to determine no additional release from any valves or hoses were possible. The release was secured by on-site emergency personnel and waste transported off-site.

column168: While moving a cubic yard box in the facility, a forklift operator punctured the box with a fork blade, resulting in a small liquid release in a containment area. Only concrete was affected; no soil or water sources were impacted. An emergency response crew was deployed. Wearing the correct personal protective equipment, the crew repacked this leaking cubic yard box and all waste materials from the cleanup into two new appropriately UN rated cubic yard boxes.The waste continued to its final destination without further incident.     This was reported to the CT DEEP at 22:01EST; # 2017-06554, operator 201.
column169: The fork lift operator involved was given retraining on the safe operation of a fork lift before being allowed operate again, with an emphasis on situational awareness and the need to operate deliberately and avoid making hasty maneuvers.

column168: At 345pm December 30, 2017 loaded tank car GATX 33378 placarded Flammable Liquid was discovered leaking product from top Protective Housing Cover o track # 57 Terminal Railroad Association of St. Louis (TRRA) Madison Yard, Madison County, Venice, Illinois.    1630 hours 12/30/2017: Emergency responders arrived on site track # 57, 18th cars from North end of track, 2 degrees F, 10 mph wind from NW. A liquid material was noted on East-Center of tank outer jacket coming from Top-Center of tank body. Closer inspection from Top Operating Platform indicated material was coming from the bottom side of tank Protective Housing Cover. During inspection of valve arrangement located under Protective Housing Cover discovered liquid material misting from Sample/Point valve. At this time handle turned clock wise ¼ turn stopping the release of material. Other fittings located in the same area were inspected and no defects noted. Area off release was observed for approximately 15 minutes with no further release noted.
column169: Recommend shipper review loading and inspections procedures for transportation of placarded materials.

column168: While loading waste into a tank vehicle, the driver/operator noticed the rear door seal weeping. The driver/operator, already wearing the appropriate personal protective equipment, discontinued the loading process, and took immediate measures  to contain the drip with spill pads. The release impacted only the spill tray on the vehicle, and asphalt; no soil or water sources were affected. The rear door latches on this unit were tightened more fully, and the loading process was able to be completed without further incident. The waste generated from this small cleanup was placed in the correct waste stream for disposal.     This amount of this release fell below the State Reporting requirements.
column169: The driver/operator was received a disciplinary action for the release. In addition, he received retraining on vacuum truck operations, with an emphasis on completing a thorough pre-trip inspection of the rear door sealing surfaces and rear door latch tightness before use.

The spill occurred during the end of the offload and was caused by the driver in using too much air pressure. He was using between 28-30 PSI when the spill occurred. He stated that his hoses were vibrating like they were empty so he went inside to check the receiving tank and that is when he discovered that product was pouring out of the top of the customer’s tank. His first response was to close the shut-off valve on the tank but could not because of the product spilling around that area. He then went to the trailer and shut the valve which stopped the leak.
column169: Awareness messages have been sent to our entire fleet of drivers reminding them to never exceed 15 PSI for any unload following this incident. Schneider found that the individual driver responsible for the incident violated our company policies and therefore terminated his employment.

column63: No UN ratings found on drum
column168: During a routine inspection, facility personnel noticed a small release from a drum in 10-day storage. The release occurred in a concrete containment area; no soil or water sources were impacted. A field service crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment was dispatched to over-pack the drum into a correctly rated UN salvage over-pack drum. The waste generated from the cleanup was also placed in the over-pack drum. This drum continued to its final destination without further incident.     It was determined that drum did not have a visible UN rating, and the pinhole that caused the release was likely due to internal corrosion, deterioration, or incompatible waste.     This release fell below the State of Ohio reporting threshold.
column169: The driver who picked up this drum was given retraining on package inspection, with an emphasis on checking for a visible UN specification on packages containing hazardous materials. The generator of this drum was also contacted, made aware of the issue, and asked to retrain its staff on the proper container selection and thorough pre-loading inspection of packages when shipping hazardous materials.

column168: LEAKER WAS CALLED OUT BY PEN 12 SUPERVISOR NICK CLESARI. DESIGNATED RESPONDER VICTOR DUARTE AND RMP RONNIE RIVAS RESPONDED TO THE CALL. RONNIE RIVAS ARRIVED FIRST TO THE SCENE AND IMMEDIATELY SMELLED A STRONG ODOR. VICTOR ARRIVED WITH THE SPILL CART AND COULD ALSO IMMEDIATELY SMELL THE ODOR. THE ODOR IMMEDIATELY AFFECTED VICTOR WHO BEGAN TO HAVE A SLIGHT HEADACHE. RONNIE PUT ON PPE AND APPROACHED THE PACKAGE WITH DECISION TREE AND IDENTIFIED THE SPILL. RONNIE THEN BAGGED THE SPILL AND BY THAT TIME THE ODOR BEGAN TO AFFECT HIM AS WELL. THE SPILL WAS MOVED TO A VENTILATED AREA AND RONNIE NOTIFIED PE TO CONTACT OUTSIDE RESPONDER BECAUSE HE AND VICTOR BECAME IRRITATED BY THE SMELL.
column169: OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR SHOULD BE CALLED IMMEDIATELY BEFORE MOVING THE PACKAGE.

column168: On December 26, 2017, a DOT403 tanker containing UN1247 Methyl methacrylate monomer, stabilized (3, PGII) was found leaking due to an unknown cause. Approximately 0.5-gallons released to the inside of a bucket. The bucket was placed under the drip by the driver upon discovery. A contractor was dispatched who complete a tank transfer. The salvaged material was transferred into a new tanker and the impacted absorbents and debris were over packed and taken offsite for proper disposal. The empty tanker was taken offsite and is currently undergoing a full inspection to find the cause of the leak.

column168: CMV DRIVER ROUNDED A CURVE ON HIGHWAY 15 IN LOUISIANA IN ROUTE TO KROTZ SPRINGS REFINERY WHEN HIS TRAILER TRACKED OFF THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY ENTERING THE SOFT SLOPED SOIL CAUSING THE TRAILER TO PULL THE UNIT DOWNHILL AND RESTING ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. AS THE TRAILER PULLED THE TRACTOR OVER THE HILL THE BACK OF THE TRACTOR FRAME MADE CONTACT WITH THE UNDERSIDE OF THE FRONT OF THE TANK TRAILER CAUSING A PUNCTURE IN THE BODY OF THE TRAILER. WHEN THE UNIT CAME TO REST THE DRIVER DETECTED A SMALL LEAK OF CRUDE OIL AND CONTAINED THE LEAK WITH ABSORPTION PADS. LESS THAN 3 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASED.    THIRD PARTY REMEDIATION (OMI ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO TRANSFER THE CRUDE OIL TO ANOTHER TANKER AND PERFORM CLEAN-UP.
column169: CARGO TANK VEHICLE SAFETY AND ROLLOVER PREVENTION TRAINING WILL CONTINUE TO BE ADMINISTERED TO ALL COMMERCIAL VEHICLE OPERATORS.    THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT HAS BEEN SHARED WITH ALL EMPLOYEES DURING THE 1Q18 SAFETY MEETINGS. DRIVERS WERE BRIEFED ON THE TIME OF DAY, ROAD CONDITIONS, AREA LOCATION, AND POSTED SPEED LIMIT COMBINED WITH PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE INCIDENT SCENE. DRIVERS WERE THEN ASKED TO SHARE THEIR THOUGHTS AND HOW THIS INCIDENT MAY HAVE OCCURRED, THEIR OPINION OF ROOT CAUSE, WHAT THEY PERSONALLY WOULD HAVE DONE DIFFERENTLY, WAS IT PREVENTABLE OR NON-PREVENTABLE, AND THEY WERE ABLE TO SHARE THEIR THOUGHTS ON THIS ACCIDENT. THERE WAS MUCH OPEN DISCUSSION AMONG THE DRIVERS DURING THE SAFETY MEETING ULTIMATELY HEIGHTENING THE AWARENESS OF ROLLOVER PREVENTION.

column168: ON 12-15-17 AT 1626 HOURS OFFICERS RESPONDED TO NEW BAY BRIDGE ROAD INTERSECTION OF TELEGRAPH ROAD, FOR A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT WITH POSSIBLE FATALITY. ARRIVED ON SCENE AND PRICHARD FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MOBILE FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ON SCENE.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK (MCINTYRE) WAS ON SCENE AND WAS ASKED TO GO TO THE SIDE AWAY FROM THE ACCIDENT DUE TO THE FUEL LEAKAGE FROM THIS TRAILER DUE TO THE IMPACT. THERE WERE TWO WITNESSES THAT WERE ON SCENE, PAUL WYATT AND DR. CHARLOTTE HESTER. THEY WERE ASKED FOR THEIR CONTACT INFORMATION AND TOLD THEY WOULD RECEIVED A CALL TO WHAT THEY WITNESSED. THEY THERE WERE ASKED TO LEAVE THE SCENE DUE TO SAFETY ISSUES WITH THE LEAKING DIESEL FUEL.   DRIVER #1 SEEMED UNRESPONSIVE DUE TO HER HAND THAT COULD BE SEEN IN THE DRIVER WINDOW STICKING UP AND NOT MOVING, IT APPEARED THAT IT WAS A FEMALE HAND BUT AT THE TIME COULD NOT ID WHO IT WAS TILL THE VEHICLE WAS MOVED FROM UNDER VEHICLE #2.  MOBILE FIRE AND PRICHARD FIRE TOOK CONTROL OF THE SCENE DUE TO THE LEAKING DIESEL FUEL. PITTS AND SONS HEAVY WRECKER AND PITTS AND SONS FLAT BED WRECKER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO BE ABLE TO LIFT THE TRAILER AND PULL THE MINI VAN FROM UNDER THE TRAILER.  DRIVER #1 WAS IDENTIFIED AS ABOVE LISTED DRIVER. IT APPEARED THAT THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING AT A HIGHER THAN POSTED SPEED LIMIT WHEN CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE TRAILER.  DRIVER #2 WAS QUESTIONED AND STATED THAT HE HAD THE GREEN LIGHT AND TOOK SOMETIME BEFORE HE WAS IN THE ROADWAY DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF HIS LOAD. THAT AS HE WAS JUST ABOUT TO TURN ONTO NEW BRIDGE ROAD HE HAPPEN TO LOOK IN HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR HE NOTICE THE MINI VAN HIT THE TRAILER.  THE WITNESS BOTH WERE TALKED TO ON A LATER DATE AND FILLED OUT WITNESS STATEMENT FORMS, WHICH STATED THEY WERE ALSO AT THE LIGHT AT TELEGRAPH ROAD WAITING TO TURN ONTO NEW BAY BRIDGE ROAD. THAT WHEN IT TURNED GREEN THE TRUCK BEGAN TO PULL OUT AS THEY THEN DID AND WAS HIT BY THE MINI VAN THAT DID NOT STOP FOR THE RED LIGHT.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: While loading a van trailer of waste for the purposes of consolidation, a forklift driver saw he drum he was moving was punctured by the sharp edge of a metal trailer wall that had suffered unknown damage; this damaged trailer wall cut a 10 inch slice in the drum, leading to a release of 25g onto the trailer floor and into a facility containment catch basin; no soil or water sources were impacted. An emergency crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment was dispatched, and cleaned up the trailer and catch basin. The damaged drum was over-packed into a suitable salvage over-pack drum with the correct UN specifications, along with the waste generated from the cleanup.     The New York State DEC was contacted spill # 1708957.
column169: The facility forklift operator was given retraining on van trailer inspection, with an emphasis on making sure all trailer floor and wall surfaces are free from protrusions, nails, and damage which could puncture waste containers.

column168: THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS OPERATOR ERROR. THE DRIVER HAD COMPLETED FILLING AND WENT TO CARRY THE HOSE BACK TO HIS TRUCK WHEN THE HOSE SLIPPED FROM HIS HANDS AND BEFORE HE COULD PICK IT UP APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF RESIDUAL DIESEL THAT WAS IN THE HOSE SPILLED ON THE GROUND. THE DRIVER USED HIS SPILL KIT TO LAY DOWN ABSORBENT ON THE SPILLED DIESEL AND ENSURED THAT THE DIESEL WAS CONTROLLED.
column169: IN ORDER TO PREVENT RECURRENCE THE DRIVER WENT THROUGH REFRESHER TRAINING TO ENSURE PROPER TECHNIQUE IS USED. ALL DRIVERS WERE ALSO REMINDED OF THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPERLY CARRYING THE HOSE. A TRAINING REFRESHER PROGRAM AND OPEN DISCUSSION HUDDLES ARE GREAT TOOLS TO DECREASE THE FREQUENCY OF RECURRENCE.

column168: Carrier driver was performing a pre-trip inspection and noticed hazmat dripping from the discharge valve on the CMTV.  A subsequent inspection determined that moisture in the CTMV froze in the internal and external valves preventing full closure.  Driver placed sorbent pads and bucket under the leak and an emergency response contractor, wrapped the discharge valve with pads so the CTMV could be moved back into the shipper's facility.  The release lasted about 4 hours.     Quality Event #67463.

column168: Hilco Transport Driver was directed off main highway (US 52) by law enforcement because of a previous accident because Road was closed. As Hilco Transport driver attempted to maneuver the detour at a very slow rate of speed he was forced to make a tight right turn immediately past a railroad crossing. As he attempted the tight right turn the tank trailer right tires tracked across a ditch at the edge of the road. Once the loaded tank trailer tracked off the paved road into the ditch area the trailer flipped onto its right side coming to rest at the edge of the road and railroad track. No product was released. No spill. Persons who live near the accident location were evacuated as a precaution. No release of product.
column169: Ensure drivers are aware of where their trailer tires are tracking to avoid equipment tracking off edge of road.

column168: ERTS was notified of a release of Food grade phosphoric acid from a tanker transfer. The caller has reported that only about 5 gallons of the product has release. The caller stated that due to the cold temperatures a pressure relief vale was frozen shut and was not working properly. Product released from the valve impacting the asphalt pad. Caller stated that the valve didn't need to be replaced. ERTS has contacted Environmental works for the cleanup. The impacted pavement was cleaned with absorbents all waste was containerized into 5 - 55 gal poly drums for nonhaz waste and staged onsite until the profile is approved for pickup/ disposal.

column168: OUR DELIVERY VAN WAS INVOLVED IN A HEAD ON COLLISION CAUSED BY THE OTHER DRIVER LOSING CONTROL ON SLICK ROADS. THE SIGNIFICANT IMPACT CAUSED THE MOUNTAINS POINTS TO BE TURN THROUGH THE FLOOR AND THE PIPING AND VALVES WERE HEAVILY DAMAGED CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO VENT. PRODUCT WOULD HAVE DUMPED AND VAPORIZED WITHIN A COUPLE OF MINUTES.
column169: THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE IMPACT AND RESULTING DAMAGE MAKE IT IMPOSSIBLE TO SPECULATE AS TO HOW WE COULD MAKE CHANGES THAT COULD PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IF THE SAME TYPE ACCIDENT OCCURS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: ANDY MEDINA, OPERATIONS MANAGER, HARCROS DALLAS: HOWARD KNIGHT LEFT THE PASADENA BRANCH ON 12/20/2017 AT 4:10 PM. TRAVELING SOUTH ON 16TH ST AND TURNING NORTH(LEFT) ONTO EAST BOUND WHARTON WHEEMS ROAD TO GET ONTO STATE HWY 146, THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TURNED OVER ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE AT 4:23 PM. ANDY OHLER , DISTRICT MANAGER, HARCROS DALLAS AT 4:51 THERE WAS AN INCIDENT. I CALLED ANDY MEDINA FOR A LOCATION . I WAS CLOSE BY AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 5:10PM. MET ASST FIRE CHIEF DONALD LADD, LAPD OFFICER J. TRIPPER AND WALKED THE SCENE. TRUCK WAS LYING ON ITS SIDE - CAB WAS PARTIALLY ON STREET MOST OF THE TRAILER WAS LAYING ON THE GRASS. I KNEW WHAT WAS ON THE TRUCK WITHOUT NEEDING TO SEE THE BOL, AS IT HAD JUST LEFT OUR FACILITY (11 TOTES OF SODIUM ALUMINATE 38%). FLUIDS WERE POURING OVER THE CURB AND OUT THE ENGINE. THEY HAD ALREADY PLACED ABSORBENT ON THE STREET TO PREVENT FURTHER RUNOFF INTO THE STORM DRAIN. THEY ALREADY HAD AN SDS OF THE PRODUCT AND WERE NOT CONCERNED ABOUT A FIRE HAZARD. THEY ASK ABOUT OPENING THE BACK DOOR, I ADVISED THAT THEY DID NOT OPEN THE BACK DOOR WITHOUT PROPER PPE. THEY AGREED TO WAIT FOR HAZ MAT RESPONSE. WAS ASKED IF WE HAD RESPONDERS IN ROUTE - AT THAT POINT ADVISED THAT WE WERE CONTACTING PIER AND SHOULD HAVE RESPONDERS DIRECTLY. JORGE WITH HARCROS PASADENA CONTACTED PIER AND WAS TOLD 1-2 HOURS BEFORE THEY COULD UPDATE US ON AVAILABILITY. WHILE ON SITE WE MET GARY BABB OF RANGE 3 ENVIRONMENTAL WHO WAS READILY AVAILABLE AND WAS CAME AND PLACED MORE SECURE BLOCKS TO STORM DRAINS. RESPONDERS VACUUMED UP ALL THEY COULD GET OUT OF THE GRASS AND OFF THE STREET. THEY PUMPED OUT THE DIESEL TANKS - DURING THAT PROCESS WE ASKED ABOUT TRANSFERRING THE TOTES. THEY WERE USING A 1 INCH PUMP. THEY ASKED IF WE COULD PROVIDE CONTAINERS FOR TRANSFERRING THE PRODUCT, SO I WENT TO THE PLANT AND WITH THE HELP OF THE SECOND SHIFT BROUGHT 10 TOTES TO THE SITE WITH A TWO INCH PUMP AND HOSES. WE REMOVED THE FOUR TOTES THAT DID NOT RUPTURE AND PLACED THEM IN A ROLL OFF BOX AND TRANSPORTED TO THE PASADENA PLANT. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE UP-RIGHTED ABOUT 12:30 AM - EMPTY TOTES WERE REMOVED BEFORE EQUIPMENT WAS MOVED FROM THE SCENE. ADDITIONAL PRODUCT WAS VACUUMED UP. I LEFT APPROX 1:00 PM. I, JORGE GUERRA, WAREHOUSE MANAGER AT HARCROS PASADENA, WAS ON VACATION WHEN I RECEIVED A CALL FROM ANDY MEDINA AT 4:35 PM. I WAS ADVISED THAT HIS DRIVER HOWARD KNIGHT WAS JUST INVOLVED IN A ROLLOVER ACCIDENT. I IMMEDIATELY CALLED WAREHOUSE TO CHECK HOW LONG IT’S BEEN SINCE HE LEFT AND WHAT WAS LOADED. I THEN RECEIVED A CALL FROM PETE LADELL FROM SAIA, HE ADVISED ME OF THE SITUATION AND LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT. I THEN BEGAN TO RECEIVE CALLS FROM DAN JOHNSON, VINAY NAIR AND ANDY OEHLER. I ADVISED THEM ALL THAT I WAS IN ROUTE TO OFFICE TO GET SOME NEEDED DOCUMENTS. I ARRIVED AT THE OFFICE AT 5:00 PM AND I RETRIEVED A COPY OF THE SDS AND DOT 5 PART DRUG TEST FORM. I THEN PLACED CALL TO AIG AT APPROXIMATELY 5:21 PM AND MADE THE INITIAL REPORT
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE (CMV) WAS IN ROUTE TO MAKE A NORMAL DELIVERY OF GASOLINE. THE CMV WAS GOING EAST ON BEITNER RD., SLOWING, APPROACHED A RAIL ROAD TRACK. THE PASSENGER VEHICLE WAS WEST BOUND ON BEITNER RD. CROSSED THE CENTER LINE STRIKING THE CMV IN THE LEFT FRONT, RESULTING IN THE CMV JACKKNIFING AND LEAVING THE ROADWAY, SLIDING DOWN AN EMBANKMENT. THE TRUCK TRACTOR ENDED UP AGAINST SOME TREES. THE TANKER TRAILER BROKE LOOSE FROM THE TRUCK TRACTOR AND ROLLED OVER ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE. DURING THE JACKKNIFE A FUEL TANK BRACKET ON THE TRUCK TRACTOR BROKE AND PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE LOWER RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE TANKER 4 INCHES LONG, 1.5 INCHES WIDE RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF GASOLINE.     HAZMAT RECOVERY COMPANY, NORTHERN A-1 WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE BY GRAND TRAVERSE COUNTY SHERIFF. NORTHERN A-1 ARRIVED ON SITE ABOUT 22:00 TO START RECOVERY. OVERSIGHT OF THE SPILL REMEDIATION IS UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND GRAND TRAVERSE COUNTY. THE CLEAN UP IS STILL IN PROGRESS.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

HAZMAT RECOVERY COMPANY, NORTHERN A-1 WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE BY GRAND TRAVERSE COUNTY SHERIFF. NORTHERN A-1 ARRIVED ON SITE ABOUT 22:00 TO START RECOVERY. OVERSIGHT OF THE SPILL REMEDIATION IS UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE MICHIGAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND GRAND TRAVERSE COUNTY. THE CLEAN UP IS STILL IN PROGRESS.

column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY WHEN A CAR PULLED IN FRONT OF HIM CUTTING HIM OFF. BRAKES WERE APPLIED QUICKLY TO AVOID COLLISION CAUSING THE CARGO TO SHIFT FORWARD IN TRAILER. DRIVER PROCEEDED TO A SAFE LOCATION TO INSPECT THE CARGO IN THE TRAILER. WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE BACK DOOR OF THE TRAILER HE SAW THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT EVIDENT ON THE FLOOR. DRIVER CLOSED DOORS AND CALLED DISPATCH. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT SLOWLY LEAKING OUT OF THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. POLICE AND FIRE WERE CALLED AT THIS TIME AND THE COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN WAS STARTED. ONCE POLICE AND FIRE ARRIVED AND GAVE US A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF WHAT WAS GOING ON IT WAS DETERMINED THAT WE NEEDED TO CONTACT OUR CONTRACTED CLEAN UP COMPANY TO HANDLE THE MANAGEMENT AND CLEAN UP OF THE SCENE. THEY WERE CALLED AT 5:15PM. CLEAN HARBORS (CONTRACTOR) ARRIVED ON SCEN AT 8:00PM AND GET INTO THE TRAILER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A TOTE WAS LEAKING IN THE TRAILER. IT WAS ALSO DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE OTHER TOTES AND DRUMS DAMAGED AND THE INTEGRITY WAS COMPROMISED BUT NOT LEAKING. THEY CONTAINED THE LEAKING TOTE AND PRECEDED TO PUMP ALL DAMAGED TOTE AND DRUM PRODUCT TO NEW TOTES AND DRUMS. ONCE THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN TRANSFERRED INTO NEW TOTES AND DRUMS THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED. THE AREA ON THE GROUND WAS CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED AS WELL.   THE DURATION OF THE LEAK IS ESTIMATED TO BE 13 HOURS. ONCE FOUND THE LEAKING TOTE WAS CONTAINED AND IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 25 GALLONS HAD RELEASED OUT OF THE TRAILER AND THE TOTAL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS WHICH WAS MOSTLY CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER. INCLUDED IS THE INCIDENT REPORT FROM CLEAN HARBORS.
column169: AFTER AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER DID NOT PROPERLY INSPECT AND ASSURE THAT THE PRODUCT WAS SECURED AND LOADED CORRECTLY IN TRAILER BEFORE LEAVING THE SHIPPERS LOCATION.   THIS DRIVER AS WELL AS ALL OUR DRIVER WERE BROUGHT INTO THE OFFICE BETWEEN JANUARY 12TH AND 18TH FOR OUR REFRESHER TRAINING ON LOADING AND SECURING ALL SHIPMENTS LOADED INTO TRAILERS INCLUDING HAZ-MAT SHIPMENTS.

column168: Our driver was northbound on I-25 east frontage road when other motor vehicle was traveling east on hwy 60. Other driver was intoxicated and failed to stop and striking our unit on the left rear drive axle then continuing back underneath the trailer tearing off the pump, lander gear, under run protection and damaging the grind out/fitting box. No injuries, both vehicles were towed from the scene. Cause of release from the impact to the pump on the trailer, release amount was minimum. The environmental impact was moderate and was cleaned up by Colorado DOT.

column168: DRIVER WAS BACKING INTO A CUSTOMERS DRIVEWAY TO MAKE A HEATING OIL DELIVERY. THE DRIVEWAY SLOPES GRADUALLY DOWNHILL AND THEN BACK UP AGAIN AROUND TO THE REAR OF THE HOUSE. AS HE STARTED TO CUT TO THE LEFT. HE NOTICED THAT HE WAS NOT ALIGNED PROPERLY AS THE DRIVEWAY WAS COVERED WITH SNOW. HE THEN EXITED THE VEHICLE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION AT WHICH TIME HE SPREAD SOME SAND AROUND THE REAR WHEELS. THE DRIVER THEN GOT BACK INTO THE TRUCK AND ENGAGED THE DIFFERENTIAL LOCK. HE TURNED THE WHEEL SLIGHTLY TO STRAIGHTEN OUT THE TRUCK AND BEGAN TO BACK UP. THE WHEELS STARTED TO SPIN WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO SLIDE RIGHT AND INTO THE DITCH RESULTING IN THE TRUCK ROLLING ONTO IT’S SIDE. THE REAR COMPARTMENT WAS PUNCTURED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 1500 GALLONS. THE MAINE DEP AND ST. GERMAIN – COLLINS WERE CONTACTED. ST-GERMAIN – COLLINS WAS ALSO CONTRACTED TO COMPLETE CLEAN-UP.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS ISSUED A WRITTEN WARNING AND TERMS OF CONTINUED EMPLOYMENT WHICH MOST BE ADHERED TO. HE WAS NOT TERMINATED AS HE HAD AN EXEMPLARY SAFETY RECORD PRIOR TO THIS INCIDENT. THIS INCIDENT HAS ALSO BEEN ADDED TO THE COMPANY SAFETY MEETING AGENDA FOR DETAILED DISCUSSION WITH ALL DRIVERS.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Inadequate Procedures
column168: THIS DRIVER IS AN OWNER OPERATOR LEASED TO OUR COMPANY. HIS COMPANY IS DOUBLE TROUBLE TRUCKING INC. DOUBLE TROUBLE INC’S EQUIPMENT CONFIGURATION IS A TRUCK WITH BODY TANK ATTACHED AND A PUP TANKER TRAILER. THE DRIVER HAD PICKED UP HIS LAST LOAD OF THE DAY. DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS HE WAS ONLY ABLE TO UNLOAD THE PUP TRAILER. WHEN HE TRIED TO UNLOAD THE BODY TANK ON THE TRACTOR HE DISCOVERED THE FIRE VALVE WAS APPARENTLY FROZEN, THE TEMPERATURES AT THE TIME WHERE IN THE SINGLE DIGITS. HE LEFT THE OFFLOAD FACILITY WITH 105 BBLS OF OIL LEFT IN THE BODY TANK. THE DRIVER DID NOT CONTACT DISPATCH OR ANYONE IN MANAGEMENT BEFORE LEAVING THE FACILITY FOR PROPER INSTRUCTIONS. HE DROVE APPROXIMATELY 20 MILES TO NEW RAYMER, CO AND BORROWED A LOCAL SHOP AND SPACE HEATERTO THAW HIS FIRE-VALVE. AT SOME POINT AROUND 2:30 AM HE PULLED ON THE VALVE HANDLE TO SEE IF IT WAS THAWED, WHEN HE PULLED THE HANDLED, PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND IGNITED BY THE SHOP HEATER. HE WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE BUILDING AND ROLL ON THE GROUND TO PUT OUT THE FLAMES. AT THAT TIME, HE CALLED 911. THE BUILDING AND THE TRUCK WHERE TOTALED IN THE FIRE ALONG WITH THE CARGO.  SOME OF THE CARGO RAN ONTO THE GROUND WITH A WATER OF FOAM MIX FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WAS DIKED UP TO CONTAIN RUNOFF. AT THIS TIME CLEANUP HAS NOT BEEN DONE, ONLY CONTAINMENT, DUE TO FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THE DRIVER SUSTAINED 1ST AND 2ND DEGREE BURNS AND IS STILL IN THE BURN UNIT FOR FURTHER CARE
column169: OUR COMPANY HAS NEVER USED AN OPEN HEAT SOURCE TO THAW FROZEN VALVES ON A TRAILER CONTAINING FLAMMABLE MATERIALS. THE OWNER OPERATOR SHOULD HAVE MADE PHONE CALLS AS HE WAS SUPPOSED TO DO IN THIS TYPE OF SITUATION. HE WOULD HAVE BEEN DIRECTED TO COME TO OUR FACILITY FOR HELP, NOT TO ACT ON HIS OWN. THIS ACCIDENT SHOULD AND WOULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED. WE HAVE SINCE DRAWN UP SPECIFIC PROTOCOL FOR A SITUATION LIKE THIS AND RE-TRAINED ALL DRIVERS IN PROPER WAYS TO HANDLE FROZEN VALVES.   A COPY OF NEW PROCEDURE IS ATTACHED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON DECEMBER 27, 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30PM THE STATE POLICE CONCORD RECEIVED MULTIPLE PHONE CALLS OF A TRACTOR TRAILER THAT WAS OVERTURNED ON TOP OF ANOTHER VEHICLE ON ROUTE 495 SOUTH PRIOR TO EXIT 31 IN LITTLETON, MA. ONCE THE STATE TROOPERS ARRIVED ON SCENE LITTLETON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WESTFORD FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ALREADY ON SCENE TENDING TO BOTH PARTIES INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT. THE OPERATOR OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED TO UMASS MEDICAL IN WORCESTER, MA WITH VARIOUS INJURIES FROM THE CRASH. THE OPERATOR OF THE OTHER VEHICLE INVOLVED IN THE CRASH WAS TRAPPED UNDERNEATH THE TANKER AND WAS REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE AND TRANSPORTED TO UMASS MEDICAL WITH NON-LIFE THREATENING INJURIES. BOTH HAZMAT AND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WERE CALLED AND ON SCENE FOR CLEAN UP OF FUEL AND OIL SPILLAGE DUE TO THE CRASH. BOTH VEHICLES INVOLVED IN THE CRASH WERE TOWED FROM THE SCENE.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: THIS WAS THE MAIDEN VOYAGE FOR THIS TRUCK. IT WAS A USED TWO COMPARTMENT TANK, THAT WE JUST ACQUIRED FROM THE PURCHASE OF KENNY STRICKLAND INC. WE MOUNTED IT ON A NEW 2019 KW CHASSIS. THE TANK WAS TRANSFERRED FROM AN OLD OUT OF SERVICE TRUCK, THE TRANSFER WAS PERFORMED BY EMPIRE TANKER REPAIR, THEY TRANSFERRED THE BODY AND PERFORMED ALL THE TESTING. THEY PERFORMED A 5 YEAR VKIP AND DID ANY REPAIRS TO BRING IT INTO COMPLIANCE (INVOICE ATTACHED) AND ALSO PERFORMED THE ANNUAL LEAK TEST FOR ARB. ALL THIS WORK WAS DONE ON 10/27/17, PLUS THEY CERTIFIED THE TEST FOR THE COLTON SHELL RACK ON 11/2/17. ON 12/22/17, THE TRUCK WAS TRANSFERRED FOR OUR EL CAJON SHOP TO OUR CALIMESA YARD TO BE PUT INTO SERVICE. OUR DRIVER WENT TO COLTON COMMUNITY RACK ON SOUTH RIVERSIDE AVE, TO LOAD A FULL LOAD CLEAR ULS CARB DIESEL. HE LOADED HIS TRAILER AND THEN THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK TANK HAS TWO COMPARTMENTS, HE LOADED THE REAR COMPARTMENT FIRST AND WAS FINISHING THE FRONT COMPARTMENT WHEN THE LEAK WAS FOUND. HE STARTED LOADING THE FRONT COMPARTMENT, WHEN HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A LEAK COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK UNDER THE FRONT COMPARTMENT. HE STOPPED THE PUMP AND WAS LOOKING UNDER THE TRUCK, TRYING TO SEE WHERE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM. HE NOTIFIED THE TERMINAL OPERATOR AT KINDER MORGAN, THEN HE CALLED HIS DISPATCHER ON CALL. THE TERMINAL OPERATOR CAME TO OVER HELP. WE COULDN’T FIGURED OUT WHY THE TANK WAS LEAK, WHEN IT WAS JUST CERTIFIED BY EMPIRE TANKER REPAIR FOR SERVICE. WE CONTACTED DALE MARCHANT, THE OWNER OF EMPIRE TANKER FOR HELP. OUR DISPATCHER AND FLEET MGR. WERE IN CONTACT WITH THE OPERATOR JACOB HORNSBY FROM KINDER MORGAN, ON WHAT WE NEEDED TO DO AND HE SAID, DON’T WORRY ABOUT IT, WE’VE MADE THE NECESSARY “BARE BONES” REPORTING. ONCE DALE FROM EMPIRE TANKER SHOWED UP, HE DETERMINED THAT A PLUG WAS LEFT OUT AFTER THE TESTING WAS DONE! AT THAT DALE, TOLD SOCO AND KINDER MORGAN, THAT HIS COMPANY WAS TAKING FULL RESPONSIBILITY AND WOULD COVER ANY COST OR FINES. ON 12/27/17, A FOLLOW UP CALL WAS MADE BY OUR COO TO KINDER MORGAN AND WAS TOLD TO ASK FOR GENE (909-877-2141). GENE SAID THEY WERE WORKING DIRECTLY WITH EMPIRE TANKER AND NOTHING ELSE WAS NEED FROM SOCO.
column169: FIRST OF ALL, I WISH THE KINDER MORGAN OPERATOR WOULD HAVE TOLD ME, I NEED TO REPORT THE SPILL TO THE NRC. I’M VERY FAMILIAR WITH THE PROCESS AND WOULD HAVE BEEN COMFORTABLE MAKING THAT CALL. WHEN IT COMES TO KINDER MORGAN, THEY HAVE VERY STRICT RULES IN PLACE AND IF WE DON’T FOLLOW THEM, WE CAN BE KICKED OUT FOR A SET AMOUNT OF TIME. SO, WHEN THE OPERATOR TELLS US THAT HE’S GOT IT HANDLED, I THOUGHT IT WAS ALL TAKEN CARE OF, BUT NOW I KNOW THAT’S NOT THE CASE. IN FUTURE, IF SOMETHING EVER HAPPENS LIKE THIS AGAIN, I WILL BE SURE TO REPORT IT MYSELF.     SECOND OF ALL, WE TRUSTED THIS CERTIFIED SHOP (EMPIRE TANKER REPAIR) TO PERFORM THE PROPER TEST AND CERTIFY THE TRUCK WAS READY FOR OPERATIONS. THIS SPILL WOULD HAVE OCCURRED, NO MATTER WHERE THE FIRST LOAD WOULD HAVE TAKEN PLACE, WE’RE JUST GLAD IT WAS IN A PLACE THAT HAD TOTAL CONTAINMENT AND NOTHING LEFT THE PROPERTY, ALSO, WE ARE GLAD THAT THIS INCIDENT DIDN'T HAPPEN ON A PUBLIC STREET, WHERE THIS COULD HAVE BEEN A BIGGER PROBLEM.     WE ARE TAKING STEPS, TO FIND A NEW SHOP TO PERFORM OUR ANNUAL LEAK TEST AND ANY NEW CONSTRUCTION THAT MIGHT NEED TO BE DONE.

column168: ON 12/15/17 (21:35PT), THE S. SEATTLE HUB ADVISED LARS THAT TOP UNIT JBHU281085 ARRIVED LEAKING A THICK YELLOW LIQUID ONTO THE BOTTOM CONTAINER (JBHU305366), AS WELL AS THE WELL CAR. THE CONTAINERS WERE DERAMPED AND PLACED IN A SAFE HAVEN AREA.  LARS CONTACTED NRC ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND AND REMEDIATE THE LEAKAGE. JBHU281085 WAS WAYBILLED CONTAINING NONA PLACARD AMOUNTS OF BATTERIES: UN2794 AND UN3480. THE ACTUAL LEAKING MATERIAL WAS FROM ONE OF NUMEROUS UNDECLARED HAZMAT MATERIALS IN THE LOAD. THE LEAK WAS UN1263 TM PAINT, SPECIFICALLY AN EPOXY RESIN MATERIAL. THE SOURCE WAS A TIGHTLY STRETCHWRAPPED PALLET OF 3 GALLON METAL PAILS, WHICH ONE LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM LAYER. APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART WAS UNDER THE PALLET, ON THE FLOOR, 1 GALLON WAS ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE BOTTOM CONTAINER AND ½ GAL CONTAINED ON THE RAILCAR. THE MATERIAL WAS HARDENED OR HARDENING AT TIME OF CLEANUP.   THE CARGO WAS RELOADED AND 2 DRUMS OF RECOVERED MATERIALS PLACED AT THE REAR FOR SHIPPER HANDLING. LARS ADVISED JB HUNT CARGO CLAIMS (RICHARD) OF ADDITIONAL UNDECLARED HAZMAT PRODUCTS IN THE LOAD, NOT DECLARED BUT OF REPORTABLE AND PLACARDING QUANTITIES.
column169: JB HUNT HAS BEEN ADVISED TO CONFIRM PROPER PLACARDING WITH THEIR CUSTOMER: SAIA MOTOR FRT PRIOR TO PICKUP. REVIEW WITH SAIA, THE DISCREPANCIES OF THEIR WAYBILLING TO ENSURE FUTURE SHIPMENTS ARE ACCURATE AND COMPLETE.

column25: UNIVAR/KINDER MORGAN ST. LOUIS LIQUIDS TERMINAL
column168: AT 1330 DURING LOADING OPERATIONS THE OPERATOR VERIFIED WITH THE DRIVER IF ALL THE VALVES WERE CLOSED ON THE TRAILER INSTEAD OF VERIFYING HIMSELF BEFORE LOADING THE TRUCK. DURING THE LOADING PROCESS A RELEASE OF 800 GALLONS OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE (CAUSTIC SODA) CAME OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF LOAD VALVE OF THE TRAILER FILLING THE CONTAINMENT. THE CONTAINMENT HELD 600 GALLONS AND THE OTHER 200 GALLONS WENT OUT OF CONTAINMENT ONTO THE GRAVEL AND CONCRETE AREA. TOTAL DURATION BEFORE THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AROUND 6 TO 7 MINUTES BEFORE THE OTHER OPERATOR IN THE AREA WALKED AROUND THE CORNER OF THE CONCRETE WALL BY TANK 2 TRUCK PAD AND SEEN THE RELEASE COMING OUT OF THE OFF LOADING PORT OF THE TRAILER AND RAN UP TO THE INTERNAL VALVE HANDLE OFF TO THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER CLOSING THE VALVE AND STOPPING THE RELEASE. THE OPERATOR ON TOP OF THE TRAILER STOPPED LOADING OPERATIONS AND NOTIFIED KM MANAGEMENT. ALL INTERNAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE WITHIN KINDER MORGAN TO ADVISE THEM ON THE SITUATION. PROPER NOTIFICATIONS WAS MADE TO AGENCIES AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEANUP WAS PROVIDED BY A THIRD PARTY SERVICE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES TO PERSONNEL AND NONE OF THE SPILL MADE IT NAVIGABLE WATERWAYS.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING AND A MEETING WITH ALL OPERATORS TO MAKE SURE THEY UNDERSTAND THAT VERIFICATION OF THE VALVES ON ALL TRUCKS/TRAILERS ARE TO BE CHECKED AND VERIFIED CLOSED PRIOR TO LOADING. SAME WITH INBOUND TRUCK LOADS, CHECK ALL PAPERWORK, SEALS, LOAD INFORMATION AND TRAILER INFORMATION BEFORE THEY OFF LOAD ANY PRODUCT. ADDITIONALLY, WE HAVE STARTED PUTTING SEALS WITH NUMBERS ON ALL TRUCKS LEAVING THE FACILITY.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: American Airlines routinely moves aircraft hazmat parts by truck and by air.  A fuel unit had been moved by truck from DFW Airport to the Tulsa Base where the part was delivered to the main warehouse shipping/receiving location.  Before the part was binned, a pick ticket was issued to dispatch the fuel unit to American Airlines LGA Airport.  The Materials Logistics Specialist (MLS) found the box but did not check the contents.  Rather, the MLS saw a sticker on the outside of the box that indicated "Not Regulated by Highway" and made the error that the part was non-hazardous.  FedEx shipping documents were prepared and the box containing the fuel unit was inadvertently offered to FedEx for transportation by air.  Upon receipt of the box at LGA airport, a Stores MLS detected the odor of fuel and notified Management of the discrepancy.
column169: Additional training and follow-up by management may prevent recurrences.  American has a robust shipping system that will prevent such errors but personnel must use the system.  The MLS in Tulsa did not notice that the pick ticket indicated "Hazardous Material" in the banner.  Some banners are not at the top of the pick ticket due to programming at the time.  Efforts are underway to move the "Hazardous Material" banner to a consistent location at the top of the pick ticket for all Hazardous Materials parts and supplies.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: American Airlines needed a LPC Bleed Waste Actuator for an aircraft out of service in TPA.  No replacement parts were readily available.  A decision was made to Loan/Borrow a part from JetBlue Airlines.  The part was trucked from Orlando Airport (MCO) to TPA where it was decided it was no longer needed as another means was developed to repair the aircraft.  Efforts were then made to expedite the part to back to JetBlue.  Since the part had been transported by truck from Orlando, it was identified as non-hazardous by ground with no Hazmat paperwork or markings to indicate that it was hazardous.  Therefore the Store Materials Logistics Specialist (MLS) who was new to the position made the erroneous determination that the part was new and therefore contained no fuel.  The MLS was focused on expediting the part to American Airlines in Charlotte (CLT) for processing to return to JetBlue.  As a result, the fuel unit was shipped on American Airlines Flight 1810 undeclared.  The error was discovered by an MLS in CLT when the part was opened and being processed to return to JetBlue.
column169: Additional training is required to ensure diligence to procedure of always opening the box/inspecting the part to determine if it is hazardous based on the fact that it is used and/or smells of fuel.  American is in the process of reviewing our procedures to address these types of failures.

column168: Univar's driver had approximately 250-300 gallons delivered off the mini bulk trailer before a leak was discovered on his hose at the valve. column168: A small spill of bleach occurred when disconnecting a hose at a customer site.  Less than 5 gallons of product was lost to a contained area at a customer site.  Material was cleaned up.  No injuries during the incident. The valve stem handle for product transfer was damaged during a time prior to the delivery involved in the release.  The valve handle on the trailer was repaired in our garage.  The valve design allows the handle to be turned 360 degrees rather than 90 degrees.  During the handle reinstall, the handle was placed on the valve stem in the wrong direction so when the handle was in the 'closed' position, the valve was actually in the 'open' position.  The valve body does not allow for visual confirmation of the valve position from the exterior of the valve.
column169: The product transfer valve was replaced with a valve that has a turn radius of less than 360 degrees.  In addition, should the handle need to be removed, its closed position will be marked prior to removal to ensure proper replacement.

column168: While offloading in Catlettsburg, KY the driver noted wisps of HF coming from the stem of the crossover valve in the unloading hose. The driver tightened the stem nut and the leak was stopped. The estimated time of the wisp leak was a few minutes until the stem nut could be tightened. The offloading was then resumed without further incident.
column169: Upon return of the cargo tank to the plant, the maintenance team completed a 5 why investigation. The crossover valve which is where the leak was noted,  is a 1” cam-tite valve which should be in the closed position during offloading. In order for this valve to leak through the stem while closed it would require a double failure. The valve would have to leak past the ball seat and also through the stem seals. The valve was found to have the wrong size nut clip installed. This issue has been identified previously, and there are corrective actions currently in place to address it on all 15 affected trailers.  This includes a 30 day torqueing program and a new style lock washer for the packing nuts. The valve was taken to a 3rd party facility for testing of the seats The valve was pressured up to 80 psi of air and held for 5 minutes and did not leak.

Driver team performed all required off-loading process checks. Leak test of unloading hose did not identify any leaks. After several minutes of offloading, wisping of HF vapors were seen originating from the unloading hose of the cargo tank. Unloading ceased, and hose was inspected. A small gash was discovered in the hose approximately 30-31 inches from the flange on the end of the hose that connects to the hard pipe.  Another off-load hose was brought to the location to successfully unload the cargo tank.  The damaged hose was rinsed with water and a soda ash solution. Blind flanges were installed and hose was secured in the hose trough for the trip back to the plant. Upon close examination of the Resistoflex hose and root cause analysis by the plant reliability team determined the following:   • The hose was cut apart to view all the layers.  The inner Teflon liner had a pinhole opening.  The inside of the outer carcass had splayed cracking as if a blunt force had been applied.  The outside of the carcass had the visible split or gash. • At the point of the gash, there is an open space between the cargo tank and bumper whereby road debris could possibly be kicked up and strike the hose.   • The team attempted to recreate the damage on another similar hose and could do so only with extreme force using a mallet.  Attempting to cut the hose with a box cutter also failed. • Temperatures at the time were unusually cold.  However, the location of the gash was near the hard pipe connection.  This point is away from the points of the hose which are normally twisted and otherwise manipulated.  If there were failure due to extreme temperature, it would have been at those points.  Additionally, the hose is rated to -20°F and has not otherwise failed due to temperature extremes.
column169: The resulting corrective actions from the RCA process are:  • Replace current Resistoflex hoses with HFIPI industry approved Resistoflex steel over steel, Teflon lined hoses.  Hoses are on order and will be replaced as cargo tanks return to plant. • Bolting a shield to the trailer to cover the open space so the hose won’t be struck by road debris.  Shield installation will occur on planned maintenance scheduled for the cargo tank. • Procedures will be modified to include hand-over-hand visual inspections of hose prior to shipment and prior to unloading.
